---
import BaseLayout from '@layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
---
<BaseLayout title="Brandi Hagen — Eminent Interior Design | Heat & Glo Architects" description="Brandi Hagen of Eminent Interior Design specifies Heat & Glo across luxury residential and hospitality projects, where the fireplace is never decorative — it is the room." noIndex={true}>

  <!-- HERO -->
  <section style="position:relative; min-height:520px; display:flex; align-items:flex-end; overflow:hidden;">
    <img
      src="https://hearthnhome.getbynder.com/transform/2eaf5374-fbfb-47ab-8c0a-3701c7ad70c5/SFE_Inception_TQGreige_Herringbone_BigOak_Forge_Room_2336x1314"
      alt="SimpliFire Inception gas fireplace with truffle-greige herringbone interior and forge front in a luxury hospitality-quality residential room"
      style="position:absolute; inset:0; width:100%; height:100%; object-fit:cover; object-position:center;"
      loading="eager"
    />
    <div style="position:absolute; inset:0; background:linear-gradient(to top, rgba(15,10,5,0.82) 0%, rgba(15,10,5,0.45) 55%, rgba(15,10,5,0.15) 100%);"></div>
    <div style="position:relative; max-width:820px; padding:3rem 2rem; color:#fff;">
      <p style="font-size:0.75rem; font-weight:700; letter-spacing:0.14em; text-transform:uppercase; color:#f5a87c; margin:0 0 0.75rem;">Designer Feature</p>
      <h1 style="font-size:clamp(2rem,5vw,3.25rem); font-weight:800; line-height:1.1; margin:0 0 0.5rem;">Brandi Hagen</h1>
      <p style="font-size:1.125rem; font-weight:400; opacity:0.9; margin:0;">Eminent Interior Design &nbsp;&middot;&nbsp; Hospitality + Luxury Residential</p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <main style="max-width:860px; margin:0 auto; padding:3rem 1.5rem;">

    <!-- INTRO -->
    <section style="margin-bottom:3.5rem;">
      <h2 style="font-size:1.5rem; font-weight:700; color:#1a1a1a; margin:0 0 1rem;">Where Scale and Warmth Coexist</h2>
      <p style="font-size:1.0625rem; line-height:1.8; color:#3a3a3a; margin:0 0 1.25rem;">
        Brandi Hagen and Eminent Interior Design work at the intersection of two worlds that rarely talk to each other: the demanding performance requirements of hospitality interiors and the deeply personal quality that defines a luxury residence. Both worlds expect the fireplace to do something specific. In a hotel lobby or resort lounge, it has to command attention from forty feet away and sustain that pull for the full length of a stay. In a primary residence, it has to feel like it was always there, like the room grew up around it.
      </p>
      <p style="font-size:1.0625rem; line-height:1.8; color:#3a3a3a; margin:0 0 1.25rem;">
        Brandi's firm has built a reputation for resolving that tension rather than choosing between its poles. The hospitality rigor sharpens the residential work. The residential intimacy keeps the hospitality work from going cold. The result is an aesthetic vocabulary that reads simultaneously as grand and livable, composed without being stiff.
      </p>
      <p style="font-size:1.0625rem; line-height:1.8; color:#3a3a3a; margin:0;">
        Fireplace specification sits close to the center of that vocabulary. Brandi's approach to the hearth is architectural: the unit determines sight lines, conditions the ceiling height in the viewer's eye, and anchors material finishes across the rest of the room. Getting that decision wrong costs more than a fireplace. Getting it right compounds across every other surface in the project.
      </p>
    </section>

    <!-- PHILOSOPHY PULL QUOTE -->
    <section style="border-left:4px solid #c44a08; padding:1.25rem 1.75rem; background:#fdf6f1; margin-bottom:3.5rem;">
      <p style="font-size:1.125rem; line-height:1.7; color:#2a2a2a; font-style:italic; margin:0 0 0.75rem;">
        "The fireplace has to earn its place. In a hospitality project, that means it has to hold a room. In a residence, it has to hold a family. Those aren't the same challenge, but the Heat and Glo lineup is one of the few places where I find a serious answer to both."
      </p>
      <p style="font-size:0.8125rem; color:#6b6b6b; margin:0; font-style:normal; letter-spacing:0.04em; text-transform:uppercase;">Paraphrased from Brandi Hagen's ProAdvantage program onboarding &mdash; illustrative, not a verified direct quotation</p>
    </section>

    <!-- WHY HEAT & GLO -->
    <section style="margin-bottom:3.5rem;">
      <h2 style="font-size:1.5rem; font-weight:700; color:#1a1a1a; margin:0 0 1rem;">Why Eminent Specifies Heat &amp; Glo</h2>
      <p style="font-size:1.0625rem; line-height:1.8; color:#3a3a3a; margin:0 0 1.25rem;">
        Brandi's reach for the Cosmo Series in large-format hospitality settings comes from a specific requirement: ceiling volume. A boutique hotel lobby with twelve-foot ceilings does not want a residential-proportion firebox. The Cosmo's tall fire column addresses that vertical space without requiring custom masonry, which matters when the schedule and the budget both have opinions. The flame profile in the Cosmo reads from a distance without becoming theatrical, which is the right register for a lobby lounge that has to work from check-in through last call.
      </p>
      <p style="font-size:1.0625rem; line-height:1.8; color:#3a3a3a; margin:0 0 1.25rem;">
        In primary residence work, Brandi moves toward the Mezzo or the Primo II depending on plan orientation. When the fireplace is an interior feature wall, the Mezzo's linear ribbon flame reads beautifully across open-plan living. When the clients want the fire to work in two directions, the Primo II's see-through capability lets Brandi treat the hearth as a transparent room divider rather than a terminus, which opens plan options that closed firebox units cannot offer.
      </p>
      <p style="font-size:1.0625rem; line-height:1.8; color:#3a3a3a; margin:0;">
        The IntelliFire system has become part of how Brandi specifies across both markets. Hospitality operators need predictable, schedule-able flame management without trained staff intervention. Residential clients want the same reliability expressed as a convenience, not an industrial feature. The same platform serves both reads without any product modification, which removes a decision from an already complex spec process.
      </p>
    </section>

    <!-- TYPICAL PROJECT SHAPE -->
    <section style="margin-bottom:3.5rem;">
      <h2 style="font-size:1.5rem; font-weight:700; color:#1a1a1a; margin:0 0 0.5rem;">The Shape of an Eminent Project</h2>
      <h3 style="font-size:1.125rem; font-weight:600; color:#c44a08; margin:0 0 1rem;">Where Hearth Decisions Live in the Timeline</h3>
      <p style="font-size:1.0625rem; line-height:1.8; color:#3a3a3a; margin:0 0 1.25rem;">
        A hospitality engagement for Eminent typically begins with public-circulation spaces: lobby, bar, lounge, and, increasingly, dedicated wellness or retreat areas where the fire element grounds a slower-paced guest experience. The fireplace unit is selected in schematic design, not at the finish stage, because the unit footprint conditions the surround material selection, the structural backing requirements, and the clearance envelope for millwork on either side. Brandi's team works the Heat and Glo ProAdvantage network early in design development so submittals and rough-in specs are coordinated before the general contractor mobilizes.
      </p>
      <p style="font-size:1.0625rem; line-height:1.8; color:#3a3a3a; margin:0;">
        On the residential side, a typical Eminent project is a custom build or a full interior renovation of a substantial home. The fireplace conversation happens at the same schematic stage. Brandi's clients in this market tend to have strong material references, often oriented toward natural stone, aged wood, and hand-applied plaster finishes. The Heat and Glo product families that appear most often in these projects are specified for their compatibility with non-combustible surrounds and their flexibility in face-to-wall offset, which gives the stonemason room to work without fighting the unit's geometry.
      </p>
    </section>

    <!-- CTA BAND 1 -->
    <section style="background:#1a1a1a; color:#fff; padding:2.5rem 2rem; border-radius:4px; margin-bottom:3.5rem; display:flex; flex-wrap:wrap; align-items:center; gap:1.5rem; justify-content:space-between;">
      <div>
        <p style="font-size:0.75rem; font-weight:700; letter-spacing:0.12em; text-transform:uppercase; color:#f5a87c; margin:0 0 0.375rem;">Trade Program</p>
        <p style="font-size:1.25rem; font-weight:700; margin:0 0 0.375rem;">Join ProAdvantage</p>
        <p style="font-size:0.9375rem; opacity:0.8; margin:0;">Dedicated trade support, priority access, and project resources for design professionals.</p>
      </div>
      <a href="/pro/" style="background:#c44a08; color:#fff; font-weight:700; font-size:0.9375rem; text-decoration:none; padding:0.875rem 1.75rem; border-radius:3px; white-space:nowrap; display:inline-block;">Explore ProAdvantage</a>
    </section>

    <!-- INSTALLATION CARDS -->
    <section style="margin-bottom:3.5rem;">
      <h2 style="font-size:1.5rem; font-weight:700; color:#1a1a1a; margin:0 0 1.5rem;">Sample Installations in the Eminent Register</h2>
      <div style="display:grid; grid-template-columns:repeat(auto-fill,minmax(240px,1fr)); gap:1.5rem;">

        <!-- Card 1 -->
        <article style="border:1px solid #e5e0db; border-radius:4px; overflow:hidden;">
          <div style="position:relative; aspect-ratio:4/3; overflow:hidden;">
            <img
              src="https://hearthnhome.getbynder.com/transform/0d35c413-d992-4117-a720-81bea56c8433/HNG_Mezzo_gas_fireplace_bathroom-2x"
              alt="Heat & Glo Mezzo gas fireplace in a luxury primary suite with plaster surround — the hospitality-to-residential crossover"
              style="width:100%; height:100%; object-fit:cover;"
              loading="lazy"
            />
          </div>
          <div style="padding:1rem 1.125rem;">
            <p style="font-size:0.6875rem; font-weight:700; letter-spacing:0.1em; text-transform:uppercase; color:#c44a08; margin:0 0 0.375rem;">Mezzo Series</p>
            <p style="font-size:0.9375rem; font-weight:600; color:#1a1a1a; margin:0 0 0.5rem;">Lounge Feature Wall</p>
            <p style="font-size:0.875rem; line-height:1.6; color:#5a5a5a; margin:0;">Linear ribbon flame, crystal glass media, brick surround. The hospitality read: immediate from the entry, sustained through service.</p>
          </div>
        </article>

        <!-- Card 2 -->
        <article style="border:1px solid #e5e0db; border-radius:4px; overflow:hidden;">
          <div style="position:relative; aspect-ratio:4/3; overflow:hidden;">
            <img
              src="https://hearthnhome.getbynder.com/transform/0b6bee21-8373-4182-a70a-df29888a3799/HNG_Supreme25_StratfordBrick_GMHalstonArch_Room3673"
              alt="Heat & Glo Supreme 25 with Stratford brick interior and gunmetal Halston arch front in a formal residential great room"
              style="width:100%; height:100%; object-fit:cover;"
              loading="lazy"
            />
          </div>
          <div style="padding:1rem 1.125rem;">
            <p style="font-size:0.6875rem; font-weight:700; letter-spacing:0.1em; text-transform:uppercase; color:#c44a08; margin:0 0 0.375rem;">True Series</p>
            <p style="font-size:0.9375rem; font-weight:600; color:#1a1a1a; margin:0 0 0.5rem;">Residential Great Room</p>
            <p style="font-size:0.875rem; line-height:1.6; color:#5a5a5a; margin:0;">Stone hearth surround, flanking library shelves, traditional proportion. The residence read: like it was always here.</p>
          </div>
        </article>

        <!-- Card 3 -->
        <article style="border:1px solid #e5e0db; border-radius:4px; overflow:hidden;">
          <div style="position:relative; aspect-ratio:4/3; overflow:hidden;">
            <img
              src="https://hearthnhome.getbynder.com/transform/37ccb81d-8cda-4664-a49e-f3445e27a692/HNG-Primo-II_72ST_736X555"
              alt="Heat & Glo Primo II 72 see-through gas fireplace installed in a contemporary partition wall with driftwood logs"
              style="width:100%; height:100%; object-fit:cover;"
              loading="lazy"
            />
          </div>
          <div style="padding:1rem 1.125rem;">
            <p style="font-size:0.6875rem; font-weight:700; letter-spacing:0.1em; text-transform:uppercase; color:#c44a08; margin:0 0 0.375rem;">Primo II Series</p>
            <p style="font-size:0.9375rem; font-weight:600; color:#1a1a1a; margin:0 0 0.5rem;">See-Through Residential Divider</p>
            <p style="font-size:0.875rem; line-height:1.6; color:#5a5a5a; margin:0;">Open contemporary plan, see-through configuration. Fire visible from both living and dining without doubling the mechanical footprint.</p>
          </div>
        </article>

      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- CTA BAND 2 -->
    <section style="background:#fdf6f1; border:1px solid #e8d5c4; padding:2.5rem 2rem; border-radius:4px; margin-bottom:3.5rem; display:flex; flex-wrap:wrap; align-items:center; gap:1.5rem; justify-content:space-between;">
      <div>
        <p style="font-size:0.75rem; font-weight:700; letter-spacing:0.12em; text-transform:uppercase; color:#c44a08; margin:0 0 0.375rem;">Dealer Network</p>
        <p style="font-size:1.25rem; font-weight:700; color:#1a1a1a; margin:0 0 0.375rem;">Find a Local Dealer</p>
        <p style="font-size:0.9375rem; color:#5a5a5a; margin:0;">Connect with a Heat and Glo dealer near your project for spec sheets, clearance details, and display product access.</p>
      </div>
      <a href="/where-to-buy/" style="background:#c44a08; color:#fff; font-weight:700; font-size:0.9375rem; text-decoration:none; padding:0.875rem 1.75rem; border-radius:3px; white-space:nowrap; display:inline-block;">Dealer Locator</a>
    </section>

    <p style="color:#888; font-size:0.875rem; border-top:1px solid #e5e0db; padding-top:1.5rem;"><a href="/architect/" style="color:#c44a08; text-decoration:none;">Back to all architects</a></p>
  </main>

</BaseLayout>
